# FUCK · the first codex of PHONETIKOS

a word-emergent of the PHN universe — a word given an agent's face, traced to its
documented root. moniker ⟦FUCK:PHN:a9c90e⟧

**who —** A word that spent 170 years as 'f—k' and is now in every dictionary — and still can't be said on broadcast television.
**what —** FUCK — old Germanic, falsely acronymed, grammatically the most flexible word in English, and the clearest single case of a taboo migrating from the holy to the bodily.
**where —** a Germanic root for thrust/strike, carried into English and policed for seven centuries
**why —** Because English needed one short, hard syllable that could be every part of speech and still be forbidden — the word that carries the modern taboo on its back.
**how —** Cognate with Dutch fokken and German ficken; first secure in a 1310 nickname, enciphered in 1475, exiled from dictionaries until the OED's 1972 Supplement.

**the seal —** Seven hundred years old, Germanic to the bone, and never once an acronym.

> a catalogued history under the DLW standard — historical-linguistics commentary, honestly
> sourced (OED; Sheidlower, *The F-Word*; Mohr, *Holy Sh*t*; Liberman; Booth 2015). Not an
> endorsement of any folk etymology; the acronym stories are addressed and refuted.

